default1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe ambiguity of the Police Reform and Social Responsibility Act 2011 in outlining the 
defaultroles and responsibilities 
defaultof Police and Crime Commissioners
default has
default led to variation across England and Wales in terms of 
defaultwho is involved in collaboration
default, and on what matters. 
default&#xa0;
default2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe 
defaultPACE Act 1984 acknowledged that core police and criminal justice agencies are unable to comprehend and prevent crime and disorder issues alone, and thus emphasised the need for agencies to work in partnership
default. 
defaultSince then, both voluntary and statutory partnerships between relevant agencies have been implemented, with varying degrees of success. These partnerships can be argued to have created silos within a fragmented criminal justice ‘system’, in which both overlapping and contradictory priorities, targets and funding streams exist. Police and Crime Commissioner
defaults
default are
default well placed
default to better align 
defaultsuch
default partnerships, 
defaultand rejuvenate
default joined-up
default prevention and interventio
defaultn. 
default&#xa0;
default3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe health sector has been identified as a key partner of the police. In 
defaultSouth Wales
default the Commissioner takes an analytical evidence-based approach to the role, looking to the work of 
defaultProfessor 
defaultJonathan Shepherd at a local Accident and Emergency Department who identifies 
defaultthat
default violent incidences i
defaultn the night-time economy lead
default to pressure on both the police 
defaultand
default health institutions. In 
defaultCardiff
default city centre a small triage facility is 
defaultnow 
defaultavailable on weekends, thus reducing the volume of low-severity patients needing transport to Accident and Emergency Department outside the city centre and then using resources there. 
defaultThe triage facility
default is run by staff from the police, health sector, local authorities and third sector
default,
default and the South Wales Commissioner aims to take a similar baseline approach to all Accident and Emergency Departments across 
defaultSouth Wales
default. 
default&#xa0;
default4.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultMental health is an issue that 
defaultseveral
default Police and Crime Commissioners have committed themselves to targeting
default, albeit through different collaboration
defaults
default. 
defaultThe Commissioner for Greater Manchester
default acknowledges the amount of police time it takes to administer the appropriate response for someone who is suffering from mental health problems, and has invested
default £200,000 of this year’s 
defaultbudget to partnership working wi
defaultth the NHS to develop innovations aimed at improving the current response.
default 
defaultIn 
defaultStaffordshire
default,
default 
defaultthe 
defaultCommissioner held group meetings with Police Officers, PCSOs and Staff below the rank of Inspector to discuss their day-to-day working lives, and found that issues of mental he
defaultalth were 
defaultconsistently raised
default. Recording the
default details of every incident involving mental health over an eight week period proved the scale of the issue, and the complexity of agencies involved. Since then, a ‘whole system’ approach has 
defaultbeen 
defaultdeveloped with stakeholders across health, social care and the voluntary sector to ensure a timely and appropriate response, as well as 
defaultbringing mental health professionals 
defaultto the frontline, 
defaultworking alongsid
defaulte the police
default.
default 
defaultIn 
defaultAvon and 
defaultSomerset
default, the C
defaultommissioner
default states that 646 people were detained under the Mental Health Act in police cells in 2012/13, and is changing the custody landscape with the aim of having no mental health patients in police cells by April 2014. Care planning is also being improved through collaboration
default with Mental Health liaison and Diversion Services.
