default5.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe Police and Crime Commissioner for
default Northamptonshire
default is one of a few Commissioners who 
defaultcall
default for the integration of 
defaultthe three main emergency response services: 
defaultpolice, fi
defaultre and ambulance. The argument for doing so is that 
defaultit will deliver effective, efficient services of high standard and will save valuable resources to sustain the frontline by handling emergency calls only once
default a
defaultnd commanding
default resources in a joined-up way.
default 
default&#xa0;
default6.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultBoth Northamptonshire and Greater Manchester Commissioners have highlighted the lack of ‘system’ in the Criminal Justice System
default. G
defaultreater 
defaultM
defaultanchester
default Commissioner has had pragmatic discussions with the Courts, prosecutors, probation, police and other criminal justice partners about how to improve victim services. The outcomes of these meetings have already been piloted: in one 
defaultlocal 
defaultarea the police and probation are now based together to manage offenders
default,
default 
defaultas well as
default improve preventative measures; in another area, 
defaulta mult
defaulti-agency approach 
defaulthas been
default taken to counter organised crime networks, 
defaultresulting in arrests and 
defaultthe 
defaultse
defaultizure of millions of pounds worth
default of property and drugs. Agencies involved included 
defaultall 
defaultemergency services, councils, the Serious Organised Crime Agency, NHS, Her Majesty’s Revenue and Customs, and the Illegal Money Lending Team, as well as other public bodies, thus extending inve
defaultstigation into every area of a
default criminal’s life.  
default&#xa0;
default7.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSome Police and Crime Commissioners have focussed
default on
default 
defaultgaps in the protection of victims and potential victims, and the impact that private businesses have on these gaps
default. 
defaultIn Northumbria, the Commissioner has recognised that the night-time economy in Newcastle is not a safe place for the vulnerable
default,
default despite work by the local BCU and Safe Newcastle Partnership. To tackle 
defaultviolence again
defaultst
default women, 
defaultthe Commissioner has facilitated 
defaulta training
default course 
defaultfor door supervisors to learn how to assess triggers of vulnerability. The course was developed by Northumbria Police, Safe Newcastle, the local authority safeguarding and licensing teams, Tyneside Rape Crisis and the le
defaultading local door
default staff company. This company
default ensured that all their staff undertook the train
defaulting in weeks, and other security
default firms quickly
default followed, with the police present at each step. 
defaultAs a consequence 
defaultof this collaboration, and the
default gap in National Security Industry Training being acknowledged, Northumbria’s programme has become a compulsory part of the national training. 
default&#xa0;
default8.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAs well as collaborating with partners from both the public, private and voluntary sectors, some Commissioners are recognising that the Chief Constable of their force is also a partner.
default For example,
default 
defaultthe Commissioner for 
defaultSouth Wales
default refers to the Chief as a partner, recognising it as a mutually challenging relationship but with clear areas of responsibility
default.
default&#xa0;
default9.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultPolice and Crime Commissioners are also collaborating regionally on specific aspects of policing. 
defaultFive Police and Crime Commissioners in the South West have joined up to collaborate on several aspects of policing, aiming to improve efficiency and remove duplication, increase resilience, and enhance capacity, capability and flexibility. Avon and 
defaultSomerset
default, Wiltshire, Dorset, Devon and 
defaultCornwall
default, and 
defaultGloucester
default have collaborated on a dedicated counter terrorism team, police dogs and some aspects of road safety and also introduced a single, shared special branch IT intelligence system
default. 
defaultIn addition, t
defaulthese five commissioners have signed their forces up to a new Code of Ethics to help assure the public of standards of policing. The code is aligned with existing police regulations and professional standards and has been influenced by the Code of Ethics put in place when the Police Service of Northern Ireland was established. 
default&#xa0;
default10.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe establishment of the East Midlands 
defaultSpecial Operations Unit
default over a decade 
defaultago
default marked the beginning of collaborative policing
default in
default the area, which is now delivered 
defaultby this unit and the East Midlands Police Collaboration Programme. Since their election, these collaboration arrangements have been overseen by the five Police and Crime Commissioners of Derbyshire, Leicestershire, 
defaultLincolnshire
default, Northamptonshire and Nottinghamshire. Areas of policing covered by these collaborations include: serious and organised crime, major crime, intelligence, forensics and counter-terrorism, as well the
default organisational support functions
default of IT infrastructure, police legal services, training programmes, fraud and financial investigati
defaultons and the regionalisation of human resources
default data. 
default&#xa0;
default11.
default&#xa0; 
defaultPolice and Crime Commissioners and Chief Constables from Bedfordshire, Cambridgeshire and Hertfordshire have signed up to a ‘Memorandum of Understanding’ and will collaborate on specific operational and organisational functions. These include finance, fleet, estates and facilities, legal, human resources, professional standards, training, ICT, firearms licensing, custody and crime recording.
default The aim of this collaboration is to assist with safeguarding police office numbers and enhance economic efficiency of services. 
default&#xa0;
default12.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe four Welsh Police and Crime Commissioners have formed an ‘All-
defaultWales
default Commissioners’ group. Meeting quarterly, moving around the force areas, the Commissioners discuss Wales-wide strategic issues and identify common issues where they can work together. They have met jointly with stakeholders in the Drug Intervention Programme, and the Welsh Government Director of Corporate Services and Partnerships, indicating that priority is being given to these topics.
